diff:1670625278:1670119092:=69,87d68%0a%3c #foxbegin 221209-223438-262300#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Criteria for accentrism  %0a%3c -> - ziqiliu%0a%3c -> [-09.12.2022 - 14:34-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221209-223438-262300 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c What piqued my interest is the last sentence of the linked article: "Except when an employer can show that an accent makes an employee so hard to understand as to create a legitimate basis for an adverse action, an employer's discrimination against someone with a foreign accent generally constitutes national-origin discrimination."%0a%3c %0a%3c When is an accent considered to be hindering conversations? This depends heavily on the employer's opinion, which itself might be biased in a lawsuit. I would think criteria for linguistic discrimination should be more based on the employer's show or lack of respect towards the accents and the people who speak them. %0a%3c %0a%3c This reminds me of a few online anecdotes showcasing linguistic discrimination in China. The Northeastern accent of Mandarin has long been the target of bias and linguistic discrimination. People who speak this accent tend to be perceived as "vulgar", "prone to violence", and "weirdly comedic" by a large portion of the population (not only speakers of Standard Mandarin but in other accents as well). I have read about the experiences of people who got rejected in job interviews and even got ridiculed during the process. In my opinion, it's hard to fix this social issue because the bias runs deep in the history of regional discrimination. In other words, linguistic discrimination is usually a part or the derivative of some larger social problems. %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221209-223438-262300#%0a
